%%TITLE
p16 expression independent of human papillomavirus is associated with lower stage and longer disease-free survival in oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma.
%%ABSTRACT
There is limited information regarding the incidence of p16 expression, its association with human papillomavirus (HPV) and prognosis in oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC). The role of p16 in OSCC is evaluated in 215 cases using tissue microarrays (TMAs). p16 immunohistochemistry and HPV in situ hybridisation were performed on TMAs following histopathology review of 215 patients with OSCC in the Sydney Head and Neck Cancer Institute database. Thirty-seven (17.2%) cases showed p16 expression without association with HPV. p16 expression significantly decreased with increasing pT category (p=0.002). p16 expression was associated with longer disease-specific survival on univariable analysis (p=0.044) but not on multivariable analysis adjusting for depth of invasion. Amongst patients receiving adjuvant radiotherapy, patients with p16 expression had significantly longer disease-free and overall survival. p16 expression was seen in early stage OSCCs and was associated with better survival following surgery and radiotherapy. While not an independent predictor of survival, p16 may mediate its effects by contributing to reduced proliferative capacity, leading to smaller tumour size and lower invasive potential.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
The Sydney Head and Neck Cancer Institute maintains a prospective clini- copathological database of patients with OSCC undergoing primary surgical treatment with curative intent. A total of 243 patients were identiﬁed from the database (2000– 2012) after approval from the institutional human research ethics committee [Sydney Local Health District (RPAH zone) Ethics Review Committee]. The ﬁnal study population included 215 cases after exclusion of patients without archival slides and blocks for detailed histopathological analyses, those with peri-operative mortality (within 30 days of surgery) and incomplete clinical follow– up.
Clinicopathological data
Clinical and pathological data including age, gender, type of surgery, details of adjuvant therapy, local failure, regional failure or distant metastases and follow up information were obtained. The oral subsites included the labial, the buccal and gingival mucosae, the ﬂoor of mouth, the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, the hard palate and the retromolar trigone.
Histopathological analysis
The archival slides were reviewed (RG) for various histopathological features such as tumour size, depth of invasion, pattern of invasion, tumour differ- entiation, keratin production, lymphovascular and perineural invasion and bone involvement as per the conventional criteria. All tumours were

staged as per the 7th edition of the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) Cancer Staging Manual (2010) pTNM staging parameters.Histo- pathological evaluation was performed blinded to the clinical outcome and prior to tissue microarray (TMA) construction and p16 immunohistochemistry.
Tissue microarray (TMA) construction
The patients were grouped as per their pTNM category for TMA construction. TMAs were constructed using two cores of SCC, 1 mm in diameter, from the invasive front of the tumour for each case.Highly cellular areas of tumour were selected and areas with haemorrhage, necrosis or excessive keratin deposition were avoided ().
p16 immunohistochemistry
Immunohistochemistry (IHC) was performed on the Leica-BOND III automated staining platform (Leica, Germany). Tissue sections from the TMAs were cut at 3 mm thickness onto charged Superfrost Ultra Plus slides (Menzel-Glaser, Thermo Fisher Scientiﬁc, USA). Following heat- induced epitope retrieval with an EDTA based buffer, pH 9 (Leica Microsystems, Australia), tissue sections were incubated with ready-to-use Mouse anti-Human p16INK4a (E6H4) primary antibody (CINtec Histology Kit; Roche Ventana, USA). Biotin-free Bond Polymer Reﬁne Detection Kit (Leica Microsystems, Australia) was used for p16 protein detection. The reaction product was visualised with 3, 3ʹ-diaminobenzidine chromogen and enhanced with DAB enhancer before counterstaining with haematoxylin.
Strong, diffuse nuclear and cytoplasmic staining of malignant cells was considered as positive for p16 protein expression (A,B). Lack of staining or weak cytoplasmic staining of single interspersed cells, or faint diffuse cytoplasmic staining without nuclear staining was considered as negative (C). The positive control used was high grade cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN3), with established HPV infection as deter- mined by CISH (detailed below) and resultant strong, diffuse nuclear and cytoplasmic immunohistochemical expression of the p16.
HPV chromogenic in situ hybridisation (CISH)
DNA in situ hybridisation on 3 mm TMA sections was performed on fully automated Benchmark Ultra staining platform (Ventana Medical Systems, USA) using Inform ISH iView Blue Plus Detection Kit and Red Counterstain II (Ventana), according to the manufacturer’s instructions. The assay utilised the Ventana HPV III Family 16 ISH Probe cocktail, which hybridised with high risk HPV genotypes including 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58 and
66.
Cases were classiﬁed as either positive or negative. The presence of high risk HPV was scored as positive when either large, homogenous, navy blue precipitate was present (episomal pattern) or discrete, stippled navy blue dots (integrated pattern) were found within the nuclei of malignant cells. Appro- priate positive controls of high grade cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN3) and negative controls were included.
Statistical analysis
Statistical analysis was performed using Stata version 11.2 (Statacorp, USA) and SPSS version 22.0 (IBM, USA). Categorical data were analysed using the chi-square test, normally distributed continuous data using the independent samples t test, and non-parametric data using the Mann– Whitney U test. All p values were two-sided and p values less than 0.05 were considered statisti- cally signiﬁcant.
Disease-free survival was calculated from the date of surgery to date of ﬁrst disease recurrence, or to the date of death or last follow up if there was no disease recurrence. For disease-speciﬁc survival, patients who died from causes other than OSCC were censored at the time of death. Overall survival was calculated from the date of surgery to date of death or the date of last follow up. The Log-rank test was used to assess differences in survival and survival curves were generated using the Kaplan– Meier method.
Multivariable analyses were performed using Cox proportional hazards regression modelling, adjusting for the following clinically signiﬁcant vari- ables: depth of invasion (mm), N status (N0 v N+), presence of extracapsular spread and post-operative radiotherapy as per Hosmer et al.Results are reported as hazard ratios (HR) with 95% conﬁdence intervals (CI).
